1. Add Spring Boot Actuator + Micrometer

First, you need to expose metrics from your Spring Boot app.

ğŸ‘‰ In pom.xml:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-actuator</artifactId>
</dependency>

<dependency>
    <groupId>io.micrometer</groupId>
    <artifactId>micrometer-registry-prometheus</artifactId>
</dependency>


ğŸ‘‰ In application.properties:

management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=*
management.endpoint.prometheus.enabled=true
management.metrics.export.prometheus.enabled=true


Now, when you run your app, metrics will be exposed at:

http://localhost:8080/actuator/prometheus

2. Create prometheus.yml

Prometheus needs to scrape your Spring Boot metrics.

Create a file prometheus.yml in your project root:

global:
  scrape_interval: 5s

scrape_configs:
  - job_name: 'spring-boot-app'
    metrics_path: '/actuator/prometheus'
    static_configs:
      - targets: ['host.docker.internal:8080']


âš ï¸ Note:

host.docker.internal is used so Prometheus inside Docker can reach your local Spring Boot app.

If you later run Spring Boot inside Docker too, youâ€™ll use the container name instead.

3. Create docker-compose.yml

Now spin up Prometheus + Grafana with Docker Compose.

version: '3.8'
services:
  prometheus:
    image: prom/prometheus
    container_name: prometheus
    ports:
      - "9090:9090"
    volumes:
      - ./prometheus.yml:/etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml

  grafana:
    image: grafana/grafana
    container_name: grafana
    ports:
      - "3000:3000"
    depends_on:
      - prometheus

4. Start Containers

Run:

docker-compose up -d


Prometheus â†’ http://localhost:9090

Grafana â†’ http://localhost:3000

(Default login: admin/admin)

5. Configure Grafana

Log in to Grafana.

Go to Connections â†’ Data Sources â†’ Add new data source.

Choose Prometheus.

URL: http://prometheus:9090

Save & Test.

Import dashboards:

Go to Dashboards â†’ Import.

Use Spring Boot Micrometer dashboard (ID: 4701)
.

âœ… Now youâ€™ll see Spring Boot metrics (JVM, HTTP requests, DB connections, etc.) in Grafana.

ğŸ‘‰ Do you want me to also show you how to run your Spring Boot app inside the same Docker Compose file, so everything (app + Prometheus + Grafana) runs together?

You said:
does docker automatocally pull this images when up used 
ChatGPT said:

Yes âœ…

When you run

docker-compose up -d


Docker checks if the required images (prom/prometheus, grafana/grafana) are already available locally.

If not found locally, Docker automatically pulls them from Docker Hub.

If already present, it just uses the cached local image.

Example flow youâ€™ll see in terminal logs the first time:

Pulling prometheus (prom/prometheus:latest)...
latest: Pulling from prom/prometheus
Digest: sha256:xxxx
Status: Downloaded newer image for prom/prometheus:latest
Pulling grafana (grafana/grafana:latest)...
latest: Pulling from grafana/grafana
Digest: sha256:yyyy
Status: Downloaded newer image for grafana/grafana:latest
Creating prometheus ... done
Creating grafana     ... done


ğŸ‘‰ After the first time, if you just do docker-compose up -d again, it wonâ€™t pull unless you explicitly run:

docker-compose pull


or

docker pull prom/prometheus
docker pull grafana/grafana
